item.description:
Once, on a flight from Chicago to Honolulu, a sweet old Hawaiian lady and her husband sat in front of me, and both reclined their seats at the very beginning of the eight-hour trip. âExcuse me,â I said. âThatâs very uncomfortable. Is there any chance you could put your seat back up, at least partway?â
âNo!â she snapped. âWe paid for these goddamn seats, and weâll recline them if we want to.â So then everyone was angry: I was angry because I had no room, and she was angry because I passive-aggressively kicked her seat once every 15 minutesâoften enough to be annoying, but not often enough to definitely be on purpose.
[snip]
Some European airlines have begun installing seats that are slightly tilted in their natural resting state, which, anecdotally at least, helps convince passengers they donât need to tilt further. But that doesnât go far enough. Itâs time for an outright ban on reclining seats on airplanes. Iâm not demanding that airlines rip out the old seats and install new ones; letâs just extend the requirement that seats remain upright during takeoff and landing through the entire flight. (Unlike the stupid electronic-devices rules, there is an actual good reason for this regulation: Upright seats are safer in a crash, and allow for easier evacuation.) To those who say such a rule is unenforceable, I respond: Kick. Kick. Kick.

Stiles started coming to The Halemouth three years ago, back when he was an aspiring writer with a brand-new laptop and the Hales were mostly known for being the only established Pack in Northern California. These days, theyâre also known as the makers of the best espresso in Beacon Hills, which Derek feels rightly proud of considering he snarls at anyone who comes near the espresso machine without a thorough knowledge of the benefits of a conical burr over blade grinders. But anyway, Stiles. Stiles had tripped through the door at speed only to stare up at the menu for a solid ten minutes like it was written in goddamn latin or something. Derek, while known for his fucking excellent coffee, was not known for his patience. Still isnât. And so he thinks he deserves a medal for waiting as long as he had to snarl at Stiles to get on with it. What he hadnât expected was for Stiles to flail so hard heâd actually fallen over, right there in front of the counter. Derek had leaned over to make sure he wasnât dead only to be met with one of the biggest grins heâd ever seen in his life. And he lived with Laura. âHoly shit, youâre Derek Hale,â Stiles had said, like Derek was the second coming or something. âDude, I have like, a million questions for you!â Which is how Derek had found himself the unofficial go-to for Stilesâ werewolf research.
